..REFS:
EN-A20-O14-L1 A20-O14-L1
..TEXT:
|costui~: The demonstrative pronoun, normally used to
point to a position near the person spoken to, expresses the
"distance" of blindness itself, since Dante would seem to be
standing right beside the two souls who speak here, and they know
it (see vs. 5).  |'l nostro monte~: The possessive serves to
remove and distance even more the two souls, in their blindness.
..TCHR:
362
