..TEXT:
|dirvi ch'i' sia... suona~: Dante's modesty
regarding his own name is notable and suggests that the purging
of his pride on the first terrace has been effective (compare
Omberto Aldobrandeschi's modesty in the same way, ^Purg.~ XI,
60); yet clearly there remains a touch of pride, on the part of
the poet, in the "ancor" here.  The fact that Dante avoids naming
himself should prompt the reader to reflect that in fact he has
not been named as yet in the poem, although he has been
recognized by many souls as Dante Alighieri.
