..TEXT:
|Tra brutti porci~: The river passes through the
Casentino valley (see ^Inf.~ XX, 65; ^Purg.~ V, 94), and by
"porci" all its inhabitants may be intended, but the term may
contain a special reference to the Conti Guidi particularly (note
Dante's mention of members of this family in ^Inf.~ XVI, 38, and
^Inf.~ XX, 77), with a play on the name of the Porciano branch of
the family, who were lords of Porciano, a stronghold at the foot
of Monte Falterona.  |galle~: "Acorns," on which swine were
commonly fed in such wooded regions.
