..TEXT:
|tra 'l Po e 'l monte e la marina e 'l Reno~: This
is a reference to Romagna, a former province of northern Italy,
corresponding roughly to the eastern portion of the modern
Emilia.  Cf. ^Inf.~ XXVII, 29-30.  According to Dante's
definition, Romagna as a region extended from Bologna to Rimini
and from the hills of Montefeltro to the plain of Ravenna.
Tolosano, a chronicler of Faenza (who died in 1226), in a passage
quoted by T. Casini (1894), p. 2r, defines it as stretching from
the Reno to the Foglia, which falls into the sea just above
Pesaro, and from the Adriatic to the Alps.  The Reno passes about
two miles to the west of Bologna so that according to these
limits Bologna was within the confines of Romagna, which is
somewhat unusual by way of classification, though Bologna
dominated Romagnole politics in part in Dante's day.  Note that
"Po," in this verse, means the Po di Primaro.  (See Map ^1.~)
..TCHR:
899
